Sarina the Vain, held she was the fairest and more intelligent woman in all of Cormyr. She would acknowledge only one flaw, her inablility to withstand the attacks of others. To both enhance her beauty and wit, and to increase her survival she had these circlets made.
Upon striking a foe, the serrated bolt tip is known to utter random blasphemy.
Upon striking a foe, the serrated bolt tip is known to utter random blasphemy.
A beautiful drow with deadly red eyes. She appears to be some kind of spellcaster.

Its a well known fact that elves are foppish gits, barely able to lift their own swords without a limp-wristed floppy motion. It was for this very reason that these boots were forged. 

The master elven smith Yaldriirmathileh Mastiiramaeviil, spent many long hours making these boots for the elven protectors of the long forgotten court of Myth Drannor. When the kingdom fell, many of these boots were lost, some fell into the hands of those responsible for the fall, others are a prized possession from a dragons hoard. 

Perhaps the adventurer who has stumbled upon them now will use them to serve their intended purpose. Perhaps though, they have simply made another step along the road to obscurity.

Far less common than it's red cousin, these rings are only found in the hands of a lucky few mages who manage to track one down and claim it as their own.  It takes a mage of epic skill to use such a ring.
A ring of spell storage, typically used by M'elzar wizards of The Sorcere.
For those that wear a kilt and no underwear, freedom is of prime importance. This fine pouch of sealskin  satisfies this need.

"Hope is the greatest flaw that men suffer. To hope and expect betterment to just happen by the will of some god you think cares about your meaningless life is pure folly."

- Nightcloak Aleczia on the weakness of hope.
A young woman with a slight limp.

Helms such as these have only recently begun to surface in the region, however they look ancient. Relics of an old war, long forgotten and a time nearly lost, these powerful artifacts were likely worn by the champions or paragons of the people that created them.

While the original creators of these helms seem to remain unknown, they do bare an uncanny resemblance to the natives of the Mylock Hills.

Stories speak of a poor traveller, victim to a snowstorm one winter night. In the midst of frostbite and unconsciousness, he stumbled upon an isolated monastery, dedicated to Ilmater. The monks took him in, gave him shelter, food and most notably, a pair of thick, snow-wading boots.

With new-found vigor, he left the next day, boots firmly clad. Winter gave way to spring, and spring gave way to further winters, until the man was wealthy enough to return to that secluded monastery, to give his thanks for supporting him at his time of need.

To his surprise, he could not find the monastery, no matter how hard he searched the land. The blizzard returned once more during his searches, covering the land in a white blanket. One quiet night resting in his makeshift shelter, he found a dying man, frozen half to death. After feeding him and nursing him to health, he gifted the man those same boots he received years prior, and decided to build a small monastery in place of the one he could no longer find.

"Black and White, Dark and Light, see me not, within your sight."

Extremely rare, master smiths of far away notions copied the design from weapons taken from fallen Kara-Turan soldiers. The unusual weapons were carried by high ranking court assassins, and those that knew the meaning of the blade, and saw it drawn, usually did not live long enough to tell about it. Imbued with both forces of life, there is a balance to the blade that slips in, unnoticed, until it is too late.
Said to be forged of Dragon Hide, this powerful shield can protect the bearer from a great number of dangers.

In some circles of nature, a somber tradition prevails. At the passing of an agent, when their time has ultimately come, it is not uncommon that their animal companion should die with them out of supposed grief. To this end, many workers of the natural world have seen fit to burn both master and beast upon the funeral pyre, together.

From their ashes, a Great Druid then crafts a charm to be passed on to others within the circle. The bond between the two survives even in death, and their kinship empowers those who have followed in their footsteps.

The tales of these rings inevitably lead back to the Shadow Plane, though there the trail runs cold. Most local explanations will center around Shadowscape, one of exceedingly few hospitable places in the realm.

Some have held that Grandmistress Luriko of the Three Steps Academy distributes them to students who show promise. Many have suggested they were crafted at the request of the Shadowbornes, thereby being Sharran in nature. Others still allude to strange and clandestine Shadow Magic, set apart from the dire connotations of the Dark Twin's web.

Twinkling like starlight, the jeweled bauble keeps its secrets, much like those who would wear it.

A great ash tree was found growing in an ancient forest. Pure black bark and dark of leaves, its branches were exceptionally useful for the crafting of bows.

However, this practice was cut short when a group of woodcutters were found mysteriously dead under the tree, the bark stained red in their blood.  The black ash tree was soon destroyed in a fit of paranoia afterward, and now only these remain.

With some study, it can be used to unleash a small variety of Necromantic spells.

This hulking serpentine creature looks as if he could be part green dragon. Upon closer inspection, it's difficult to verify for certain, as he seems to be missing some features that most half-dragons have - namely physical traits alike that of its dragon parent. Some of his traits seem almost fiendish, in fact, especially his leathery green wings.

There is, however, something particularly dark and fearsome in his jarring red eyes...

The cry of the banshee is a nightmare to most. However, to at least one bardic palemaster from Tarkuul it was beauty. He laboured day and night trying to mimic that dreadful keening but every sword was a failure. They could scream, they could howl but none were perfect. Driven mad by his own failure, he cast the wailing swords to the sea and fell into a deep and profound melancholy that lingers to this day.

This beautiful, extremely tall humanlike creature has long, feathery wings and supple, lithe body. His visage is faded, as if but a memory of what he once was, and yet he still bears a powerful aura of kindness and goodness...

This small, swirling, constantly shifting mist of light bobs gently in the air. Deep within these mists, one can see a rainbow of changing colors. The good-hearted feel a sense of peace and joy settle over them merely by the sight of it. Those of dark heart feel a sense of longing for the life that would have been, had they only turned to good...

Before the Underkingdom, also known as "the Spires", fell to the duergar and then to the giants, the once powerful Dwarven Kingdom was known as Dornat Murr.

Among many famous weapons and armors, the dwarven guards wielded doule-sided warhammers. One side flat and able to smash their foe, but a pick on the other side to pierce through even the most sturdy of armors. Feared were those hammers who could wreak doom onto the dwarven foes.

Lucky souls can still rarely find one of those masterpieces of dwarven craftsmenship, scattered all over the isles.
This item is not for PC use. If you have somehow come into possession of this, please contact a DM to have it removed and do not use it.
The Hand of Lendys bears a vibrant and fierce countenance. Radiant dragons are well-known for their unmitigated hatred for all things evil, and this one clearly serves a higher cause...

The ceremonial garb of Waukeen's followers is shown here in characteristic form: gaudy, ornate, and overdone. A heavy, baroque cloak loaded with different precious metals worked into fine material in vibrant colors. The local high priest often carries a magical staff also decorated with precious metals and gems. Tristana serves the Kingdom of Cetha as Master of Trade.

Kobolds are a cowardly, sadistic race of short humanoids that vigorously contest the human and demi-human races for living space and food. Barely clearing 3 feet in height, kobolds have scaly hides that range from dark, rusty brown to a rusty black. They smell of damp dogs and stagnant water. Their eyes glow like a bright red spark and they have two small horns ranging from tan to white. Because of the kobolds' fondness for wearing raggedy garb of red and orange, their non-prehensile rat-like tails, and their language (which sounds like small dogs yapping), these fell creatures are often not taken seriously. This is often a fatal mistake, for what they lack in size and strength they make up in ferocity and tenacity.
This kobold looks much different from the others...

This kit contains the various tools and liquids needed for a skilled assassin to perform and execute her special underhanded techniques. Every last bit of this equipment seem engineered towards a single minded purpose; killing its target as efficiently as possible. As the assassin's skill progresses, so does the complexity of her attacks and techniques.

//OOC Note: To use these techniques, simply use the kit and select which one to use. All of these abilities have a cooldown of 60 seconds once a target has been hit by this (saving throw rolled, not successful roll). The cooldown is universal and will persist for 60 seconds even if you change which ability to use//

Braining Blow (Stun) (2 rounds, will)
Head injuries are especially traumatic, and the Assassin knows this. Heavy, blunt force dealt by a pommel or leaden arrow can temporarily stun a foe, leaving them vulnerable to a follow-up strike.

Shrill Strike (Deafness) (Turn/assassin, fort)
The importance of the sense of hearing in combat is not lost on the Assassin. An attack upon the auditory organs leaves the ears of the Assassin's foe ringing painfully.

Beshaba's Favor (-d4 all stats) (supernatural permanent, doesn't stack, will)
The Assassin becomes adept at turning disadvantage to advantage, weakness into strength, bad luck into blessed fortune. Provided, that this misfortune falls upon the Assassin's victim.

Stalker's Throat-Dart (Silence) (1 round/ assassin, fort)
Landing a blow to the throat is one of the most difficult attacks an Assassin can make. By no chance, it is also one of the most rewarding.

Induce Amaurosis (Blindness) (1 round/assassin, fort)
The Assassin knows that something as innocuous as a culinary spice can have more malign uses. Pepper, thrown into the eyes of the foe in the heat of battle, leaves them a bit burned.

Blade of Terror (Paralysis) (1 round/assassin, will save to counter)
The appalling viciousness of the Assassin's assault cows the target into submission. The assassin may make a death-attack that causes overwhelming fear to the target of this ability.

Bloodlet (Leveldrain) (supernatrual permanent stacks, fort)
The Carotid and Femoral artery are prime targets for a cutting or piercing strike. An accurate slice can cause the most extreme case of profuse bleeding: untreated, such a strike is as good as a death-sentence.

Kneecapper's Knife (Knockdown) (Rounds/3Assassin, reflex)
The legs are a promising, if difficult to hit, target. They are often more lightly armored than the torso, as even the most rigid plate armor has many joints and thin parts in its metal.

Murder (Death, death ward ignored, fort)
The most valuable and feared tool at the Assassin's disposal is not their famed agility or skill with blade or bow, but their knowledge of anatomy and flagrant disregard for the niceties of honorable combat. This attack leaves nothing about the Assassin's motives to question. A feint, a flash of steel from the shadows, or a careful shot: a strike made with the intent to bring their target down instantly, no matter the cost.

A gear heart is the component in a golem capable of executing assigned commands. It interprets controller instructions for the golem. Gear hearts are one of the necessary components found in golems of any era, along with primary storage and input/output facilities.

Early gear hearts were custom-designed as a part of a larger, usually one-of-a-kind golem.

However, this costly method of designing custom gear hearts for particular application has largely given way to the development of mass-produced gear hearts that are suited for one or many purposes. The gear heart you are holding happens to be one of the high-tech ones.

Made from ebony wood, this hand carved snake is of dark brown and black texture as the natural grain of the wood it is made from. It is carved in the style of totems of the natives of Chult. Small scales are etched into the wood and give the totem a lot of detail. To those familiar with snakes, it appears to be a black mamba. When activated, the snake tattoo coiling around Malandria's right thigh lights up and the totem coils around the shin of the same leg.

An extremely sturdy piece of wood, this branch came from the oak tree, Acorn-Leaf. Acorn-Leaf was young, as far as trees go, and had only known an Awakened life for a few decades before The Rot claimed the tree. The branch carries just a glimmer of Acorn-Leaf's awareness, a touch of druid magic keeping a whisper of sentience held within the bark.
